dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:44:*Most successful approach to date:* none has won — and as of **0.8.3 D0b (2026-06-22) the headline parity number now EXISTS** (clears this report's #1 caveat). Under the identical-answerer protocol (gpt-5.4, 606 q, $10.75; `runs/0.8.3-d0b-parity-n606.json`, `runs/0.8.3-report.md`), **FathomDB trails Mem0 by ~20–27 pp accuracy** on factoid (−0.237), knowledge_update (−0.273), multi_session (−0.200); temporal ≈ parity (−0.033). `decide_083 = NOT_REACHED` (eu7-blocked 0.896<0.90 + all classes underpowered at N≈150 — directional, not yet a formal parity ruling). The **accuracy gap ≫ the recall gap** ⇒ the deficit is largely **answer-formation** (raw bodies vs Mem0's distilled memories), not first-stage recall — so the embedder lever is ruled out (Slice 15a NO-SWAP) and parity likely needs a caller-side/offline memory-formation layer. (Earlier Slice-25 state — N=0 gold, answerer/Mem0 unavailable — is superseded by the D0b re-pin + stand-up.) (See Appendix → Agentic long-term memory + `runs/0.8.3-report.md`.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:50:**Exp 1 — Base-retrieval recall@K, dense/fused vs BM25 (LongMemEval, n=160, paired, seed 20260614, LLM-free).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:58:Fused ties BM25 on recall (R@10 delta −0.019, inside MDE) but does not beat it; fused does beat FTS-only (+0.044, the real dense contribution). Ranking quality (MRR/nDCG) still trails BM25.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:77:BM25 matched-or-beat FTS on all four classes (5–7.5pp gaps, each within per-class MDE). `multi_session` is weakest (the eventual graph-arm target).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:96:*Most successful approach to date:* the **strong lexical baseline (naive BM25)** is still the bar — nothing in FathomDB's stack has beaten it on the LLM-free recall endpoint. Among FathomDB's own levers, **fused-RRF (dense + FTS5)** is best: ties BM25 (R@10 −0.019, within MDE) and clearly beats FTS-only (+0.044). (See Appendix → IR relevance for the "tie not loss" power call and the fused-path measurement-validity caveats.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:172:*Next work:* [planned] no M1 stage-2 (a clear non-win needs no added N); M2 full graph study DROPPED; 0.8.3 D1 promotes passage_dense to a registered comparator (with the Mean→CLS fix), D2 revives index-key enrichment in fielded BM25F form; GraphRAG sensemaking (0.8.4 S1) survives on a different axis; [suggested] D1 should target bridge *composition* not just presence, and re-pre-register an MDE-feasible materiality/N.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:186:**Exp 2 — Reader swap on identical retrieval (LongMemEval, n=160 paired, LLM-judged).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:268:| **FathomDB** | **0.8.3 D0b: trails Mem0 ~20–27 pp identical-answerer accuracy** (factoid −0.237, ku −0.273, multi_session −0.200, temporal −0.033); `NOT_REACHED` (eu7-blocked + underpowered) | internal (`runs/0.8.3-d0b-parity-n606.json`) | identical-answerer, gpt-5.4, 606 q |
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:270:FathomDB **trails Mem0 on the defining end-to-end axis** — measured at 0.8.3 D0b (2026-06-22): −20…27 pp identical-answerer accuracy on 3 of 4 memory classes (temporal ≈ parity). This is **directional, not a formal parity ruling** (`decide_083 = NOT_REACHED`: eu7 0.896<0.90 blocks + every class underpowered at N≈150). The **accuracy gap ≫ the recall gap** ⇒ the deficit is largely **answer-formation** (raw bodies vs distilled memories), not first-stage retrieval — so a "parity with Mem0/Zep" claim remains unsupported, and the path to parity runs through a caller-side/offline memory-formation lever, not the in-footprint recall levers (embedder ruled out, Slice 15a). Earlier "no e2e number / N=0 gold" state is superseded.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:317:**Why accuracy is null, not low.** The primary delta in this capability is *answer accuracy*; with the answerer LLM unavailable, only Evidence Recall@K is comparable. The factoid Δ of +0.0017 is far inside any plausible MDE at this gold count, so "tie," not "win." (Cross-reference: the base-retrieval n=160 study found per-class MDE ~21pp and pooled ~11pp on the analogous LongMemEval classes, and a strong reader scored ~5× a nano reader on identical retrieval — i.e. e2e accuracy here would be reader-bottlenecked, which is precisely why the answerer choice matters before any Mem0/Zep claim.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:327:**Design, power, and the "tie not loss" call (Experiment 1).** Paired design, seed 20260614, 4 classes (factoid/knowledge_update/multi_session/temporal). Pooled MDE ≈ 11pp; per-class MDE ≈ 21pp at n=160. The fused-vs-BM25 R@10 delta of −0.019 is well inside the pooled MDE, so it is reported as a tie, not a loss. The fused-vs-FTS-only +0.044 is the isolated dense contribution. `multi_session` (0.325 fused vs 0.275 BM25) is the *only* class where fused exceeds BM25; on ranking quality fused trails BM25 by MRR −0.088 and nDCG −0.064, i.e. dense recovers recall but not rank position.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:331:**Subset/tokenizer noise in the BM25-vs-FTS ordering (Experiment 3).** Ordering is subset-dependent: the §3 n=160 cut had BM25 ≥ FTS on every class, while a later R6 n=40 cut had FTS 0.80 > BM25 0.70 pooled. This flip is attributed to FTS5's tokenizer quality vs rank-bm25 and to small-N subset variance (per-class MDE ≈ 21pp @ n=160, ≈ 15pp @ n=40), not to the `b` parameter — all per-class deltas are direction-only at these N.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:341:**Known engine defect affecting shipped dense retrieval.** `CandleBgeEmbedder` defaults to `Pooling::Mean` for CLS-pooled bge-small (`candle_bge.rs:229`), which degrades shipped dense retrieval; the eval harness is unaffected because it uses CLS pooling. The 0.8.3 D1 CLS fix changes stored vectors and therefore must re-clear the eu7 ANN fidelity floor (≥0.90; the large-run value was 0.896 < floor, shipped via a one-sided CI gate) — i.e. fixing dense ranking is coupled to a fidelity-gate re-measurement (ADJ-3). The M1 underpoweredness and graph-arm negatives are out of scope for this capability but are the reason dense, not graph, is the carried-forward lever.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:345:**Statistical confidence / power.** All three experiments are n=40 (10/class). Per-class MDE ≈ 15pp, so any single-class delta (e.g. multi_session 0.30→0.10) is direction-only, not significant in isolation. The load-bearing result that *is* robust is the graph **ON−OFF = 0.00** pooled delta, because it is a same-engine paired A/B with zero corpus/embedder variance: identical docs, identical index, identical kind=doc anti-pollution filter, only the BFS arm toggled. It reproduces both before and after the anti-pollution filter (pre-filter: graph_OFF = graph_ON = 0.60; the filter lifted both arms +0.05 equally to 0.65, leaving ON−OFF unchanged), confirming the IDF/length-norm distortion is upstream in corpus statistics, not fixable by a result-list filter. The prior base-retrieval context was n=160 (pooled MDE ~11pp, per-class ~21pp).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:359:**Cross-capability corroboration (not part of this capability's registered endpoints).** The 0.8.2 M1 study re-adjudicated graph traversal fairly on *multi-hop answer accuracy* (MuSiQue, n=300, lexically-seeded Personalized PageRank — strictly dominates raw BFS — fused with BM25, reader gpt-5.4): ppr_fusion ΔF1 = −0.0405 vs the fused-RRF comparator, 95% paired-bootstrap CI [−0.116, +0.031] (n_boot=2000), CI upper bound below the +0.04 materiality threshold → robust NO-GO, reader-invariant across three readers. This corroborates the recall negative here: the graph lever fails on both the recall and answer-accuracy axes.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:367:**Statistics on the priced verdict.** ΔF1(ppr_fusion − fused) = −0.0405, paired-bootstrap 95% CI [−0.116, +0.031], n_boot=2000, seed 0, on the ≥3-hop cell (n=144). The verdict is load-bearing on the *effect size + CI*, not the mechanical gate: `decide()` returns NO_GO formally via the POWER gate (power_ok=False *by construction* — the ≥3-hop cell n=144 ≪ the 1165 the whole-rule power-sim requires; this is expected/correct for a stage-1 cell). The hop-trend slope (−0.013) is *not* significantly negative; it simply shows no positive dose-response. ΔEM is also negative (ppr 0.3194 vs fused 0.3542). The "pwrfix" power-sim further showed the rule is underpowered even at N=1165 (P(GO)≈0.45 at materiality 0.04) — moot under a robust reject, but a flag for 0.8.3 re-registration (ADJ-1).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:380:**Metric-definition math.** ≥3-hop F1/EM are pooled over the 144-question hard cell. ΔF1 is paired (same questions, treatment vs comparator). gets-all-bridges@10 = fraction of questions whose *complete* gold bridge set appears in top-10; F1|all-bridges conditions answer-F1 on that complete-set event. Per-hop slope is OLS of ΔF1 on hop-count {2,3,4}.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:390:**Statistical confidence (both experiments).** N=160, class-balanced (≈40/class). Per-class MDE ≈ 21pp; pooled MDE ≈ 11pp (seed 20260614, paired design). Therefore the −0.019 fused-vs-BM25 deltas (both recall and answer) are *well inside* the MDE — read as "tie/faithful pass-through," not a significant loss. Per-class orderings (e.g. KU fused 0.500 > BM25 0.475 > FTS 0.350; multi_session BM25 0.250 > fused 0.200 > FTS 0.150) are individually within per-class MDE and so are direction-only; their *consistency* across recall and answer axes is the credible signal, not any single cell. Note an ordering instability documented elsewhere: §3 n=160 had BM25 ≥ FTS, while a later R6 n=40 subset had FTS 0.80 > BM25 0.70 — attributed to tokenizer/implementation and subsample, not a real reversal.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:398:**Scope / what is *not* measured here.** These two experiments measure judged + substring *accuracy*, not answer-F1; answer-F1 is the registered endpoint of the separate multi-hop graph adjudications (0.8.2 M1, MuSiQue), which belong to a different capability and use a different reader (gpt-5.4) and a paired-bootstrap CI / power-gate / materiality-threshold decision rule not applicable to these recall-reader runs. No confident-wrong guard was separately evaluated for these LongMemEval runs. Data artifacts: `0.8.1-p0a-base-e2e-n160-gemini31pro.json`, `0.8.1-p0a-fused-e2e-n160-gemini31pro.json`, and (reader-swap) `p0a_base_n160_gemini31pro.json`.
