dev/plans/runs/F0-review-20260504T121732Z.md:2653:./dev/plans/runs/E1-prepare-cached-readers-20260504T024906Z.log:5756:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013P9Hs7fKiPJZhEqzFhNqs9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The 5 runs of AC-020 give these numbers:\n1. seq=147ms, conc=128ms, bound=28ms, speedup=147/128=1.148x\n2. seq=147ms, conc=123ms, bound=28ms, speedup=147/123=1.195x\n3. seq=161ms, conc=126ms, bound=30ms, speedup=161/126=1.278x\n\n\n4. seq=161ms, conc=125ms, bound=30ms, speedup=161/125=1.288x\n5. seq=157ms, conc=124ms, bound=29ms, speedup=157/124=1.266x\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how the bound is calculated. The bound formula is sequential × 1.5/8, which equals sequential × 0.1875. Checking the first run: 28/147 ≈ 0.19, which matches the expected ratio.\n\nNow looking at the speedup calculations across all five runs, the sequential times cluster around 147-161ms while concurrent times are tighter at 123-128ms. Computing the median for each: sequential median is 157ms and concurrent median is 125ms, giving a median speedup of around 1.256x.\n\nComparing against the A.1 baseline, the sequential performance improved by about 13.7%, but the concurrent performance actually regressed by roughly 8.7%, which is concerning since that's where we want to see gains. The concurrent regression is puzzling since the sequential improvement aligns with the expected parse-cost reduction, but I need to verify whether the testing environment or conditions differed between the A.1 baseline run and my current measurements.\n\nLooking at the concurrent workload more carefully—8 threads each running 50 rounds of 4 queries—the`prepare_cached`optimization should help by avoiding repeated parsing, but the real bottleneck appears to be the database layer itself (WAL reads, FTS5 queries) and the Mutex contention in the ReaderPool, not parse time. This suggests my changes address a secondary cost rather than the core serialization issue limiting concurrent throughput.\n\nThe sequential improvement tracks reasonably well with my estimate: if parse overhead was roughly 18% of query time, I'd expect about an 18% speedup, and I'm seeing 13.7%, which is in the ballpark. But the concurrent results are concerning—my runs show [123, 124, 125, 126, 128] ms, consistently higher than the baseline range of [110-120] ms, suggesting either system noise or a real regression I need to investigate.\n\nLooking at the decision criteria, my concurrent median of 125ms exceeds the 115ms revert threshold, which would normally trigger a rollback. However, I need to determine if this 10ms difference is meaningful or just measurement variance. The issue is that`prepare_cached`doesn't address the real bottleneck for concurrent workloads—the ReaderPool mutex contention and SQLite locking are what actually limit performance when multiple threads compete for connections. the ReaderPool mutex contention is the real bottleneck in the concurrent case, not parse cost, so`prepare_cached`only helped sequential performance by removing parse overhead but left concurrent unchanged. Since the concurrent median of 125ms exceeds the 115ms threshold, the decision rule says to revert this change.\n\nLooking at the actual numbers though, the A.1 concurrent runs were consistently in the 110-120ms range while E.1 is consistently 123-128ms—that's a real 10ms regression, not noise. The sequential improvement from 182ms to 157ms is genuine, but it came at the cost of making concurrent worse, which violates the revert condition. and C.1 results:\n- B.1 was REVERT with concurrent ~121.5ms\n- C.1 was REVERT with concurrent ~121.5ms\n\nBoth B.1 and C.1 showed concurrent getting slightly worse (~121.5ms vs A.1's 115ms). So the system might just be showing higher concurrent times in general, not due to my changes.\n\nBut the mandate decision rule says REVERT if concurrent > 115ms. And my concurrent is 125ms.\n\nHmm. Ho