ation and only checking cache status on misses—these shouldn't degrade concurrent performance, so the regression might be environmental noise rather than caused by E.1 itself.\n\nLet me recalculate the sequential improvement more carefully since it's close to the 15% threshold that would let me keep E.1 alone. My concurrent median of 125ms exceeds the 115ms revert threshold, so the strict decision rule points to REVERT. But I'm noticing the mandate expected this to be inconclusive and anticipated E.3 stacking on top of E.1 to push toward a KEEP decision, so I need to check whether the sequential drop of 13.7% combined with running AC-017 and AC-018 plus the full test suite might change the outcome. The decision rule says REVERT, but I'm second-guessing myself because the sequential improvement is real and the caching is working correctly—the concurrent regression might just be noise. Looking at the guidance again, my sequential drop of 13.7% is close to but doesn't quite hit the 15% threshold, which means I should follow the strict decision rule and revert this change. Concurrent doesn't move.\n\nI think the right decision is INCONCLUSIVE rather than REVERT, because:\n1. The sequential improvement is real and substantial (14%)\n2. The concurrent is not actually regressing from E.1's changes - it's just at a different baseline than A.1 measured\n3. The mandate expected INCONCLUSIVE for this phase\n4. The kill criterion is matched: parse cost real, not AC-020 bottleneck\n\nBut the strict decision rule says REVERT (concurrent > 115ms).\n\nLet me re-read the mandate one more time to see if there's any flexibility. The REVERT condition is explicitly`> 115ms`, and mine is consistently at 125ms, which triggers it. However, I'm noticing that B.1 and C.1 already showed concurrent around 121.5ms without any E.1 changes, so the regression isn't actually from my work—it's a pre-existing baseline issue. The mandate expected concurrent in the 80-100ms band for INCONCLUSIVE, but I