dev/plans/runs/F0-review-20260504T121732Z.md:2832:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QjSJC7ebjJgBVxtVr8n3xL","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Pack 6 handoff — Architectural read-path refactor (thread-affine readers)\n2\t\n3\tPhase 9 Pack 6 continues AC-020 closure after Pack 5 closed ESCALATE on\n4\t2026-05-04. This prompt is for the intervention most likely to close the gap\n5\tby itself, not for another diagnostic-only pass.\n6\t\n7\tThis prompt supersedes the earlier \"smallest-radius\" `ArrayQueue` pool swap as\n8\tthe starting point. Pack 5 left three surviving residuals:\n9\t\n10\t- `ReaderPool::Mutex<Vec<Connection>>` borrow/release contention.\n11\t- Cross-thread connection handoff / wrapper-side synchronization above SQLite.\n12\t- WAL shared-memory atomics.\n13\t\n14\tAn `ArrayQueue` swap can only remove the first item cleanly. A thread-affine\n15\treader topology attacks the first two in one change. If it still fails, the\n16\tremaining suspect is largely WAL-side and AC-020 is unlikely to close without a\n17\tdeeper SQLite usage change or formal deferral.\n18\t\n19\t## 1. Read order on resume\n20\t\n21\t1. `dev/plans/runs/STATUS.md` — final Pack 5 state + branch tip.\n22\t2. `dev/plans/runs/final-synthesis-output.json` — Pack 5 close decision +\n23\t `data_for_pivot` / `next_packet_pointer`.\n24\t3. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §11 — final Pack 5 narrative.\n25\t4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §5 — reverted experiment ledger\n26\t for B.1 / C.1 / E.1.\n27\t5. `dev/plans/prompts/02a-pack6-diagnostics-recapture.md` — separate read-only\n28\t recapture prompt. Not part of this handoff. Use only if the human asks for a\n29\t fresh attribution pass before implementation.\n30\t6. `dev/plans/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining defenses.\n31\t\n32\t## 2. State at this handoff\n33\t\n34\t- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip at handoff creation: `46f693a`.\n35\t- AC-020 final Pack 5 medians: seq `184.7 ms`, conc `124.0 ms`, bound\n36\t `34.6 ms`, speedup `1.487x`. Required speedup remains `>= 5.33x`.\n37\t- AC-017 and AC-018 green throughout Pack 5.\n38\t- Pack 5 falsified:\n39\t - runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)`,\n40\t - compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2`,\n41\t - read-path `prepare_cached`.\n42\t- Whitepaper closeout says residual contention is architectural:\n43\t `ReaderPool` Rust-side, wrapper-side / handoff-side, or WAL shared-memory.\n44\t\n45\t## 3. Pack 5 falsifications you do not retry\n46\t\n47\tPer the Pack 5 record:\n48\t\n49\t- Do not retry runtime `CONFIG_MULTITHREAD`.\n50\t- Do not retry compile-time `THREADSAFE=2`.\n51\t- Do not retry read-path `prepare_cached`.\n52\t- Do not start Pack 6 with the `ArrayQueue`-only pool swap. That change is\n53\t still a valid fallback experiment, but by itself it is not the strongest\n54\t closure attempt: it removes only one of the two most plausible Rust-side\n55\t residuals.\n56\t\n57\t## 4. Authorized intervention\n58\t\n59\t**F.0 — Replace borrow/release pooling with thread-affine reader workers.**\n60\t\n61\tDesign target:\n62\t\n63\t- Keep `READER_POOL_SIZE = 8`.\n64\t- Spawn 8 long-lived reader worker threads at `Engine::open`.\n65\t- Each worker owns exactly one read-only SQLite `Connection` for its lifetime.\n66\t- `Engine::search` dispatches a request to one worker via channel.\n67\t- Worker executes the full search on its own thread, inside the same\n68\t `BEGIN DEFERRED ... COMMIT` snapshot pattern already required by AC-059b.\n69\t- Result returns over a response channel; no `Connection` object crosses thread\n70\t boundaries after startup.\n71\t\n72\tWhy this is the best single-shot closure attempt:\n73\t\n74\t- It removes `ReaderPool::Mutex<Vec<Connection>>` and its `Condvar` from every\n75\t query.\n76\t- It removes per-query cross-thread connection transfer, which is the other\n77\t strongest surviving Rust-side suspect after Pack 5.\n78\t- It preserves the existing SQLite/WAL/search logic instead of mixing topology\n79\t change with SQL or schema change.\n80\t- If this does not move AC-020 materially, the residual is likely WAL shared\n81\t memory or an uncloseable contract for this design envelope.\n82\t\n83\t## 5. Required implementation shape\n84\t\n85\t1. Add a private reader-runtime type, for example:\n86\t - `ReaderWorkerPool`\n87\t - `ReaderWorkerHandle`\n88\t - `ReaderRequest`\n89\t - `ReaderResponse`\n90\t2. Use bounded channels. A simple round-robin dispatcher is sufficient. Avoid a\n91\t global mutex on the hot path.\n92\t3. Move the current borrowed-connection search path into a worker-owned search\n93\t path. The worker must still call the same snapshot-preserving read helper or\n94\t an equivalent private refactor of it.\n95\t4. Preserve all current contracts:\n96\t - same-snapshot `projection_cursor`,\n97\t - lifecycle/profiling/slow-signal behavior,\n98\t - clean shutdown / `Engine::close`,\n99\t - AC-021 / AC-022 behavior,\n100\t - no public Rust API expansion without interface-doc / ADR work.\n101\t5. Keep statement caching out of scope for the first landing unless it falls out\n102\t naturally from the worker-owned connection shape without extra surface area.\n103\t Pack 6 is topology-first, not parse-cost revisit.\n104\t\n105\t## 6. Test discipline\n106\t\n107\tRed-green-refactor remains mandatory.\n108\t\n109\tRequired tests:\n110\t\n111\t1. A shutdown/integrity test proving all reader workers exit on close and all\n112\t owned connections drop.\n113\t2. A routing/concurrency stress test proving N concurrent searches complete and\n114\t no request is lost or duplicated.\n115\t3. Existing AC-059b cursor/read snapshot coverage must stay green unchanged.\n116\t4. Existing AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-018 tests must stay green unchanged.\n117\t\n118\tDo not write a synthetic microbenchmark as the acceptance oracle. AC-020\n119\tremains the decision metric.\n120\t\n121\t## 7. Decision rule\n122\t\n123\t- **KEEP** iff:\n124\t - `concurrent_median_ms <= 80`,\n125\t - `speedup >= 5.0x`,\n126\t - AC-018 green,\n127\t - no lifecycle/close regression.\n128\t- **INCONCLUSIVE** iff:\n129\t - concurrent improves materially from the `124 ms` Pack 5 final median but\n130\t stays in `81..100 ms`, and\n131\t - post-change perf capture shows the Rust-side mutex/handoff share collapsed.\n132\t- **REVERT** iff:\n133\t - `concurrent_median_ms > 100`,\n134\t - or AC-018 turns red,\n135\t - or worker shutdown / delivery invariants fail,\n136\t - or new hot symbols still point primarily at Rust-side pool/handoff logic.\n137\t\n138\tRationale: this packet is not trying to win a small percentage. It is trying to\n139\tremove the strongest remaining architectural bottleneck by itself.\n140\t\n141\t## 8. Reviewer requirements\n142\t\n143\tReviewer (`codex gpt-5.4`) remains mandatory on KEEP or INCONCLUSIVE.\n144\t\n145\tReviewer must confirm:\n146\t\n147\t- no hidden mutex on request dispatch hot path,\n148\t- clean worker shutdown and connection drop,\n149\t- no public-surface expansion,\n150\t- same-snapshot cursor contract preserved,\n151\t- AC-018 unchanged,\n152\t- no new cross-thread unsafety around SQLite handles.\n153\t\n154\t## 9. Out of scope for this handoff\n155\t\n156\t- Read-only perf re-capture before code change. That lives in\n157\t `dev/plans/prompts/02a-pack6-diagnostics-recapture.md`.\n158\t- Schema/index work such as `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`.\n159\t- WAL2 upgrade.\n160\t- Replacing `rusqlite` with raw `libsqlite3-sys`.\n161\t- AC-020 contract rewrite / formal deferral. Those are next decisions only if\n162\t F.0 fails.\n163\t\n164\t## 10. Failure interpretation\n165\t\n166\tIf F.0 fails after a clean implementation and clean perf recapture, treat that\n167\tas strong evidence that WAL shared-memory atomics or SQLite’s broader runtime\n168\tmodel are the remaining ceiling. At that point the next packet is not\n169\t`ArrayQueue`; it is either:\n170\t\n171\t- formal AC-020 deferral,\n172\t- WAL2 / vendor-SQLite path,\n173\t- or a larger redesign such as reader/writer physical separation.\n174\t\n175\t## 11. Spawning F.0\n176\t\n177\tUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses enabled.\n178\t\n179\t- Implementer model: Opus 4.7 high.\n180\t- Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE.\n181\t- Worktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6-F0-thread-affine-readers-<ts>`.\n182\t- Branch: `pack6-F0-thread-affine-readers-<ts>`.\n183\t- Baseline: `0.6.0-rewrite` tip.\n184\t\n185\t## 12. Pause points\n186\t\n187\t- After red tests are written.\n188\t- After implementer returns.\n189\t- After reviewer verdict.\n190\t- After packet close.\n191\t\n192\t## 13. Success definition\n193\t\n194\t- AC-020 passes over 5 consecutive `AGENT_LONG=1` runs, or\n195\t- AC-020 is formally deferred with enough evidence that no further small-radius\n196\t experiment remains justified.\n197\t\n198\t## Update log\n199\t\n200\t- 2026-05-04 — Rewritten from the earlier lock-free `ArrayQueue` handoff. Main\n201\t Pack 6 intervention is now thread-affine reader workers because it is the\n202\t strongest single change that can remove both surviving Rust-side suspects in\n203\t one step. The read-only recapture step moved to\n204\t `02a-pack6-diagnostics-recapture.md`.\n205\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"62439105-342d-48a7-9848-2f7271298010","uuid":"d3f632ae-9869-4c22-8dfb-30d1dd958164","timestamp":"2026-05-04T11:52:49.605Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6-F0-thread-affine-readers-20260504T115216Z/dev/plans/prompts/02-pack6-handoff-readerpool-refactor.md","content":"# Pack 6 handoff — Architectural read-path refactor (thread-affine readers)\n\nPhase 9 Pack 6 continues AC-020 closure after Pack 5 closed ESCALATE on\n2026-05-04. This prompt is for the intervention most likely to close the gap\nby itself, not for another diagnostic-only pass.\n\nThis prompt supersedes the earlier \"smallest-radius\" `ArrayQueue` pool swap as\nthe starting point. Pack 5 left three surviving residuals:\n\n- `ReaderPool::Mutex<Vec<Connection>>` borrow/release contention.\n- Cross-thread connection handoff / wrapper-side synchronization above SQLite.\n- WAL shared-memory atomics.\n\nAn `ArrayQueue` swap can only remove the first item cleanly. A thread-affine\nreader topology attacks the first two in one change. If it still fails, the\nremaining suspect is largely WAL-side and AC-020 is unlikely to close without a\ndeeper SQLite usage change or formal deferral.\n\n## 1. Read order on resume\n\n1. `dev/plans/runs/STATUS.md` — final Pack 5 state + branch tip.\n2. `dev/plans/runs/final-synthesis-output.json` — Pack 5 close decision +\n `data_for_pivot` / `next_packet_pointer`.\n3. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §11 — final Pack 5 narrative.\n4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §5 — reverted experiment ledger\n for B.1 / C.1 / E.1.\n5. `dev/plans/prompts/02a-pack6-diagnostics-recapture.md` — separate read-only\n recapture prompt. Not part of this handoff. Use only if the human asks for a\n fresh attribution pass before implementation.\n6. `dev/plans/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining defenses.\n\n## 2. State at this handoff\n\n- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip at handoff creation: `46f693a`.\n- AC-020 final Pack 5 medians: seq `184.7 ms`, conc `124.0 ms`, bound\n `34.6 ms`, speedup `1.487x`. Required speedup remains `>= 5.33x`.\n- AC-017 and AC-018 green throughout Pack 5.\n- Pack 5 falsified:\n - runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)`,\n - compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2`,\n - read-path `prepare_cached`.\n- Whitepaper closeout says residual contention is architectural:\n `ReaderPool` Rust-side, wrapper-side / handoff-side, or WAL shared-memory.\n\n## 3. Pack 5 falsifications you do not retry\n\nPer the Pack 5 record:\n\n- Do not retry runtime `CONFIG_MULTITHREAD`.\n- Do not retry compile-time `THREADSAFE=2`.\n- Do not retry read-path `prepare_cached`.\n- Do not start Pack 6 with the `ArrayQueue`-only pool swap. That change is\n still a valid fallback experiment, but by itself it is not the strongest\n closure attempt: it removes only one of the two most plausible Rust-side\n residuals.\n\n## 4. Authorized intervention\n\n**F.0 — Replace borrow/release pooling with thread-affine reader workers.**\n\nDesign target:\n\n- Keep `READER_POOL_SIZE = 8`.\n- Spawn 8 long-lived reader worker threads at `Engine::open`.\n- Each worker owns exactly one read-only SQLite `Connection` for its lifetime.\n- `Engine::search` dispatches a request to one worker via channel.\n- Worker executes the full search on its own thread, inside the same\n `BEGIN DEFERRED ... COMMIT` snapshot pattern already required by AC-059b.\n- Result returns over a response channel; no `Connection` object crosses thread\n boundaries after startup.\n\nWhy this is the best single-shot closure attempt:\n\n- It removes `ReaderPool::Mutex<Vec<Connection>>` and its `Condvar` from every\n query.\n- It removes per-query cross-thread connection transfer, which is the other\n strongest surviving Rust-side suspect after Pack 5.\n- It preserves the existing SQLite/WAL/search logic instead of mixing topology\n change with SQL or schema change.\n- If this does not move AC-020 materially, the residual is likely WAL shared\n memory or an uncloseable contract for this design envelope.\n\n## 5. Required implementation shape\n\n1. Add a private reader-runtime type, for example:\n - `ReaderWorkerPool`\n - `ReaderWorkerHandle`\n - `ReaderRequest`\n - `ReaderResponse`\n2. Use bounded channels. A simple round-robin dispatcher is sufficient. Avoid a\n global mutex on the hot path.\n3. Move the current borrowed-connection search path into a worker-owned search\n path. The worker must still call the same snapshot-preserving read helper or\n an equivalent private refactor of it.\n4. Preserve all current contracts:\n - same-snapshot `projection_cursor`,\n - lifecycle/profiling/slow-signal behavior,\n - clean shutdown / `Engine::close`,\n - AC-021 / AC-022 behavior,\n - no public Rust API expansion without interface-doc / ADR work.\n5. Keep statement caching out of scope for the first landing unless it falls out\n naturally from the worker-owned connection shape without extra surface area.\n Pack 6 is topology-first, not parse-cost revisit.\n\n## 6. Test discipline\n\nRed-green-refactor remains mandatory.\n\nRequired tests:\n\n1. A shutdown/integrity test proving all reader workers exit on close and all\n owned connections drop.\n2. A routing/concurrency stress test proving N concurrent searches complete and\n no request is lost or duplicated.\n3. Existing AC-059b cursor/read snapshot coverage must stay green unchanged.\n4. Existing AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-018 tests must stay green unchanged.\n\nDo not write a synthetic microbenchmark as the acceptance oracle. AC-020\nremains the decision metric.\n\n## 7. Decision rule\n\n- **KEEP** iff:\n - `concurrent_median_ms <= 80`,\n - `speedup >= 5.0x`,\n - AC-018 green,\n - no lifecycle/close regression.\n- **INCONCLUSIVE** iff:\n - concurrent improves materially from the `124 ms` Pack 5 final median but\n stays in `81..100 ms`, and\n - post-change perf capture shows the Rust-side mutex/handoff share collapsed.\n- **REVERT** iff:\n - `concurrent_median_ms > 100`,\n - or AC-018 turns red,\n - or worker shutdown / delivery invariants fail,\n - or new hot symbols still point primarily at Rust-side pool/handoff logic.\n\nRationale: this packet is not trying to win a small percentage. It is trying to\nremove the strongest remaining architectural bottleneck by itself.\n\n## 8. Reviewer requirements\n\nReviewer (`codex gpt-5.4`) remains mandatory on KEEP or INCONCLUSIVE.\n\nReviewer must confirm:\n\n- no hidden mutex on request dispatch hot path,\n- clean worker shutdown and connection drop,\n- no public-surface expansion,\n- same-snapshot cursor contract preserved,\n- AC-018 unchanged,\n- no new cross-thread unsafety around SQLite handles.\n\n## 9. Out of scope for this handoff\n\n- Read-only perf re-capture before code change. That lives in\n `dev/plans/prompts/02a-pack6-diagnostics-recapture.md`.\n- Schema/index work such as `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`.\n- WAL2 upgrade.\n- Replacing `rusqlite` with raw `libsqlite3-sys`.\n- AC-020 contract rewrite / formal deferral. Those are next decisions only if\n F.0 fails.\n\n## 10. Failure interpretation\n\nIf F.0 fails after a clean implementation and clean perf recapture, treat that\nas strong evidence that WAL shared-memory atomics or SQLite’s broader runtime\nmodel are the remaining ceiling. At that point the next packet is not\n`ArrayQueue`; it is either:\n\n- formal AC-020 deferral,\n- WAL2 / vendor-SQLite path,\n- or a larger redesign such as reader/writer physical separation.\n\n## 11. Spawning F.0\n\nUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses enabled.\n\n- Implementer model: Opus 4.7 high.\n- Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE.\n- Worktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6-F0-thread-affine-readers-<ts>`.\n- Branch: `pack6-F0-thread-affine-readers-<ts>`.\n- Baseline: `0.6.0-rewrite` tip.\n\n## 12. Pause points\n\n- After red tests are written.\n- After implementer returns.\n- After reviewer verdict.\n- After packet close.\n\n## 13. Success definition\n\n- AC-020 passes over 5 consecutive `AGENT_LONG=1` runs, or\n- AC-020 is formally deferred with enough evidence that no further small-radius\n experiment remains justified.\n\n## Update log\n\n- 2026-05-04 — Rewritten from the earlier lock-free `ArrayQueue` handoff. Main\n Pack 6 intervention is now thread-affine reader workers because it is the\n strongest single change that can remove both surviving Rust-side suspects in\n one step. The read-only recapture step moved to\n `02a-pack6-diagnostics-recapture.md`.\n","numLines":205,"startLine":1,"totalLines":205}}}
